This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it introduces a new family of generative neural network models that can reproduce and generate images. It also mentions state-of-the-art results in autoencoder comparison and visual image quality, which are common topics in computer vision research. 

The paper also involves deep learning techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The use of latent vectors and statistical properties in the model suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The mutual disentanglement of decoder layers and the stable unsupervised training techniques could also place this paper in the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the mention of high-resolution data sets suggests that this paper could also belong to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category.
